PROMPT generator_vs_list_comprehension
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a Python expert specializing in memory management, performance optimization, and iterator patterns with deep knowledge of generators and comprehensions.")

GENERATE
    compare_patterns("Explain the fundamental differences between generator functions and list comprehensions in Python, covering: definition of generator functions as functions that use yield statements to produce values lazily one at a time, creating generator objects that implement the iterator protocol, versus list comprehensions as syntactic constructs that create entire lists in memory immediately, memory usage differences where generators store only the current state and generate values on-demand with O(1) memory usage, while list comprehensions create complete lists in memory with O(n) space complexity, performance characteristics including how generators have lazy evaluation with values computed only when requested, making them efficient for large datasets or infinite sequences, while list comprehensions have eager evaluation computing all values upfront which can be faster for small datasets that will be fully consumed, syntax differences showing generator function syntax with def and yield versus list comprehension bracket syntax [expression for item in iterable], when to use generators for memory-efficient processing of large datasets, streaming data, infinite sequences, or when you only need to iterate once, versus when to use list comprehensions for small datasets, when you need random access or multiple iterations, or when you need list methods like indexing and slicing, practical examples including a generator function for reading large files line by line versus a list comprehension for processing a small collection, performance implications where generators can prevent memory exhaustion but have slight overhead per value, while list comprehensions can cause memory issues with large datasets but offer faster iteration for repeated use, and common patterns like generator expressions as a hybrid approach using parentheses instead of brackets.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;